    bdr:NTF4A914BF8668537E
        a                   :Note ;
        :noteText           "Sanskrit \n\nThe Mahāvyutpatti\n\nśṛnānatīti śrāvaka (śṛṇvantīti śrāvakāḥ?)\n\nThey hear, hence they are Śrāvakas (‘Hearers’) \n\nsamyakajñāna pha lan śrā ba sintā ti śrāvaka (samyagjñānaphalaṁ śrāvayantīti śrāvakāḥ?)\n\nThey make others hear about the result of perfect awareness, thus they are Śrāvakas. (Trns. Mattia Salvini)\n\nSaddharmapuṇḍarīkasūtra\n\nkecit sattvāḥ paraghoṣaśravānugamanam ākāṅkṣamānā […] te ucyante śrāvakayānam ākāṅkṣamāṇāḥ \n\n(Kern and Nanjio, Saddharmapuṇḍarīka, p. 80.5).\n\nSome sentient beings, wishing to follow what they hear from someone else’s voice […] are explained as those who wish for the Śrāvakayāna. (Trns. Mattia Salvini)\n\nArthaviniścayasūtranibandhana of Vīryaśrīdatta\n\nbhagavato buddhasya pareṇa śrāvyanta iti śrāvakāḥ \n\nN.H. Samtani (ed.), The Arthaviniścaya-sūtra & its Commentary (Nibandhana) (Patna: K.P. Jayaswal Research Institute, 1971 [Tibetan Sanskrit Works Series XIII]\n\nŚrāvakas are so called because they are subsequently (pareṇa) brought to hear [the teaching] of the Buddha, the Blessed One.\n\nN.H. Samtani (tr.) Gathering the Meanings: The Compendium of Categories: The Arthaviniścaya sūtra and its Commentary Nibandhana (Berkeley: Dharma Publishing, 2002), p. 182.\n\nOf the Bhavagat, the Buddha, they are made to hear by someone else, thus they are ‘Śrāvakas’ (Trns. Mattia Salvini)\n\nVinayavastu\n\nEṣāgrā me bhikṣavo bhikṣuṇīnāṁ mama śrāvikāṇāṁ sūtrāntavibhāgakartrīṇāṁ yaduta kacaṁgalā bhikṣuṇī \n\nVinaya Vastu 132kha/1.21, Mithila Institute, Darbhanga, Bihar 1967\n\nThis one, oh Bhikṣus, is the foremost amongst my Śrāvikās, who perform the subdivision of the Sūtrānta: Kacaṁgalā Bhikṣuṇī. (Trns. Mattia Salvini)\n\nTibetan \n\nThe Mahāvyutpatti\n\nśrāvaka źes pa gcig tu na śṛnānatīti śrāvaka źes bya ste | de bźin gśegs pa las chos kyi luṅ ma mnos par bdag ñid kyis rtogs par (7)mi nus te ñan pa la yaṅ bya | yaṅ gcig tu na samyakajñāna pha lan śrā ba sintā ti śrāvaka źes bya ste | yaṅ dag pa’i śes pas rgyun du źugs pa la sogs pa’i ’bras bu thob pa gźan la sgrogs śiṅ thos par byed pas na ñan thos źes bya |\n\nBecause they are unable to realize by themselves without receiving the instruction of the Tathāgata , they are, for one, called 'hearers' (nyan pa)....Or, in another way, because they proclaim and cause others to hear the fruits of a stream-enterer and so on that they have attained through correct knowledge, they are called 'proclaimers who cause to be heard' (nyan thos). (Trns. David Rawson)\n\nSaddharmapuṇḍarīkasūtra\n\nmgon po de ring bdag cag nyan thos gyur, ,byang chub dam pa yang dag bsgrags par bgyi, ,byang chub pa yi sgra yang rab tu brjod, ,de bas bdag cag nyan thos mi zad 'dra\n\nProtector, today we have become proclaimers.\nWe proclaim perfect awakening.\nWe also express the sound of the awakened.\nBecause of that, we are 'proclaimers' who are similar to the inexhaustible. \n(Trns. David Rawson)\n\nJayānanda’s subcommentary on the Madhyamakāvatārabhāṣya \n\nbyang chub dam pa bla na med pa yang dag par rdzogs pa'i byang chub gzhan gyis thos par byed pas nyan thos so\n\n(sde dge bstan 'gyur dbu ma vol ra F.No. 7.a)\n\nBecause someone else makes them hear of the perfect awakening, they are called 'hearers'. (David Rawson)\n\nPāli \n\n(All the Pāli passages are from the Chattha Saṅgāyana edition, unless otherwise specified)\n\nKhuddakapāṭha-aṭṭhakathā, and also Suttanipāta-aṭṭhakathā\n\nsabbepi te vacanaṃ suṇantīti sāvakā \n\nAll of them hear the speech, thus they are ‘Hearers’ (Mattia Salvini)\n\nVisuddhimagga of Buddhaghosa\n\nbhagavato ovādānusāsaniṃ sakkaccaṃ suṇantī ti sāvakā\n\nHenry Clarke Warren (ed.), revised by Dharmananda Kosambi, Visuddhimagga of Buddhaghosâcariya ([1950] Repr. Motilal Banarsidass Publishers Private Limited, Delhi, 1989) § 7.90. \n\nThey are ‘listeners’ because they listen attentively to the instructions and teachings of the Fortunate One. (Peter Skilling)\n\nSummary of the discussion\nThe Sanskrit term Śrāvaka, and its Tibetan and Pāli equivalents, are difficult to render in English with a single expression. The main difficulty is that we find at least three different possible etymologies in traditional sources:\n\n1.\tActive and not-causative (‘they hear’)\n2.\tActive and causative (‘they make others hear’)\n3.\tPassive and causative (‘they are made to hear by others’)\n\nWe may either retain the Sanskrit Śrāvaka, or use one English term (as for example, ‘Hearer’), or use different English renderings in different contexts."@en .
    
